definition.value: A dipeptide composed of L-cysteine and L-serine joined by a peptide linkage.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamine, two L-leucine units and L-proline joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamine, L-phenylalanine, L-tryptophan and L-tyrosine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-aspartic acid and two L-glutamine units joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A glycodihydroceramide having an alpha-D-glucuronosyl group at the 1-position of the sphinganine skeleton and a (2R)-2-hydroxytridecanoyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A quaternary ammonium salt obtained by formal methylation of the tertiary amino function of 4-diphenylacetoxy-N-methylpiperidine.

The meso-form of nordihydroguaiaretic acid. An antioxidant found in the creosote bush, Larrea divaricata, it is a potent lipoxygenase inhibitor that interferes with arachidonic acid metabolism. It also inhibits (though to a lesser extent) formyltetrahydrofolate synthetase, carboxylesterase, and cyclooxygenase.
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of diphenylacetic acid and the hydroxy group of 4-hydroxy-N-methylpiperidine.
A quaternary ammonium ion where three methyl groups and one 2-phosphoethyl group are attached to the nitrogen.
A glucosylglycerol derivative consisting of a 1,2-diglyceride having an alpha-D-glucuronosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
An alpha-D-glucuronosyl diglyceride in which the acyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions are stearoyl (octadecanoyl) and palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) respectively.
A member of the class of kynurenamines that is aniline substituted at position 2 by a 3-aminopropanoyl group.
An alpha-D-glucuronosyl diglyceride in which the acyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions are (10R)-10-methyloctadecanoyl and palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) respectively.
Any organic molecule containing a C#C bond.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is the S-acetyl derivative of beta-methylthiocholine
An alpha-D-glucuronosyl diglyceride in which the acyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions are palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) and (10R)-10-methyloctadecanoyl respectively.
An acetylenic compound which a carbon of the C#C moiety is attached to a hydrogen atom.

A compound arising by replacement of one or both hydrogen atoms of acetylene (ethyne) by a metal or other cationic group. By extension, the class of acetylides includes analogous compounds derived from terminal acetylenic compound, RC#CH.
A sphingoid having the structure of phytosphingosine but with R-configuration at C-3.
A sphingolipid in which D-xylo-phytosphingosine is substituted on O-1 by an alpha-D-galactosyl group and on nitrogen by a hexacosanoyl group.

A polyketide that is a member of the manumycin family of antibiotics and exhibits strong antibacterial, antifungal, and antineoplastic activities. Isolated from from the actinomycete bacterium Streptomyces nodosus subsp. asukaensis.
An L-alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of grixazone A, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An L-alpha-amino-acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the two carboxy groups of grixazone B.
A pentapeptide composed of two L-glutamic acid units, L-glutamine and L-tryptophan joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-leucine, L-phenylalanine and L-alanine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-lysine, L-tryptophan and L-alanine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-phenylalanine and two L-glutamine units joined by peptide linkages.
A tetrapeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, two L-threonine units and L-tyrosine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-alanine and L-tryptophan joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-aspartic acid and L-isoleucine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of two L-glutamic acid units and L-isoleucine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of three L-glutamic acid units joined by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of two L-glutamic acid and one glycine residues joined in sequence.
A tripeptide composed of one L-glutamic acid and two L-cysteine units joined by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, glycine and L-tryptophan joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-isoleucine and L-phenylalanine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-isoleucine and L-serine joined by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-isoleucine and L-valine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
An acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3-hydroxy-3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)propionyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid, L-phenylalanine and L-valine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and two L-valine units joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-aspartic acid joined by a peptide linkage.
A long chain fatty alcohol that is octadecanol containing a double bond located at position 9 (the Z-geoisomer).
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and glycine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-leucine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-methionine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-proline joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-serine joined by a peptide linkage.
The N(4)-acetyl derivative of L-2,4-diaminobutyric acid
A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and L-threonine joined by a peptide linkage.
